  "In a population of 10,000 individuals, 9% show a recessive phenotype. After a new predator is introduced that preferentially targets individuals with the recessive phenotype, the frequency of the recessive phenotype drops to 1% over several generations. How has the allele frequency changed": "",
  "Initially, q² = 0.09, so q = 0.3. After selection, q² = 0.01, so q = 0.1. The recessive allele frequency decreased from 0.3 to 0.1 because individuals expressing the recessive phenotype were selectively removed from the population by predation.": "",
  "A medical geneticist notes that cystic fibrosis (autosomal recessive) affects about 1 in 2500 Caucasian newborns. Using Hardy-Weinberg, she calculates the carrier frequency. Why is this information clinically important": "",
  "If q² = 1/2500, then q = 1/50 and p = 49/50. Carrier frequency (2pq) is approximately 2(49/50)(1/50) = about 1/25 or 4%. This reveals that carriers are 100 times more common than affected individuals, important for genetic counseling.": "",
  "Two neighboring populations of the same butterfly species are separated by a river. Population A has an allele frequency of p = 0.8 for wing color, while Population B has p = 0.3. A bridge is built across the river, and extensive interbreeding occurs. After several generations, both populations have p = 0.6. What does this demonstrate": "",
  "Gene flow between the two populations through interbreeding mixed their gene pools, causing allele frequencies to converge toward an intermediate value. This demonstrates how gene flow reduces genetic differences between connected populations.": ""
